`WORK_ORDER.product_id` identifies the product to manufacture, and `INVENTORY.product_id` identifies stock records for products stored in warehouses. `INVENTORY.warehouse_id` links each stock record to `WAREHOUSE.warehouse_id`, so checking “across all warehouses” means aggregating all `INVENTORY` rows for that `product_id` without limiting to a single warehouse.

The relevant columns are:
`WORK_ORDER.work_order_id`, `WORK_ORDER.product_id`, `WORK_ORDER.quantity_ordered`, `WORK_ORDER.quantity_completed`, `WORK_ORDER.warehouse_id`;
`INVENTORY.product_id`, `INVENTORY.warehouse_id`, `INVENTORY.quantity_on_hand`, `INVENTORY.quantity_reserved`, `INVENTORY.reorder_threshold`;
and optionally `WAREHOUSE.warehouse_id`, `WAREHOUSE.warehouse_name` if you want warehouse-by-warehouse detail.

At a schema level, the check is:
find the work order, join it to inventory on `WORK_ORDER.product_id = INVENTORY.product_id`, sum inventory across all warehouses, and compare the total available stock to the work order quantity still needing fulfillment. The remaining work order quantity can be derived from `quantity_ordered` and `quantity_completed`, since the table explicitly stores both. Because inventory separately tracks `quantity_on_hand` and `quantity_reserved`, the most relevant available stock measure is the unreserved portion of stock, derived from those two columns.

So the logic is:
for a given `work_order_id`, get its `product_id`;
find all `INVENTORY` records for that `product_id` across every `warehouse_id`;
aggregate stock across warehouses;
compare aggregated available stock against the work order’s remaining quantity.

If you want the stock at the production location only, you would additionally match `WORK_ORDER.warehouse_id = INVENTORY.warehouse_id`, but that would no longer be “across all warehouses.”

What the context does not provide is any bill-of-materials or component-consumption path for determining whether there is sufficient component inventory to manufacture the work order’s product. Although `INVENTORY` can store either a `component_id` or a `product_id`, and `WORK_ORDER` is for a `product_id`, the retrieved context does not include the schema needed to derive required components per work order. So the knowledge graph supports checking product inventory for the work order’s product across warehouses, but not full material sufficiency for production inputs.
